  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a lived reality for many students and professionals who feel the weight of negative expectations about their group's abilities. Growing up in a household where my parents both held advanced degrees, I've seen firsthand how deeply ingrained biases can shape educational outcomes. When I was in college, I remember a moment during a group project where a classmate remarked, 'You're so smart for a girl,' which made me feel both validated and anxious. That's the essence of stereotype threat: the fear that your performance might confirm a negative stereotype about your group. In my experience as a full-time student in Washington DC, where STEM fields are highly competitive, this phenomenon disproportionately affects women, people of color, and first-generation students. The psychological toll is real—it can lead to decreased confidence, avoidance of challenging tasks, and even dropping out. Should we address it? Absolutely. The solution isn't just about awareness but actionable strategies like implicit bias training for professors, creating mentorship programs that foster belonging, and designing curricula that highlight diverse contributions to STEM. For instance, incorporating stories of underrepresented scientists into textbooks can help students see themselves in the field. My own experience with baking and board games taught me the value of patience and collaborative problem-solving—skills that are equally vital in STEM. By addressing stereotype threat head-on, we don't just improve individual outcomes; we build a more inclusive ecosystem where everyone has the opportunity to thrive. It’s not just a matter of fairness—it’s about unlocking potential that’s been systematically overlooked.",
